org.knime.core.node.util.filter

Class NameFilterConfiguration

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.knime.core.node.util.filter.NameFilterConfiguration
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Cloneable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DataColumnSpecFilterConfiguration, FlowVariableFilterConfiguration

    public class NameFilterConfiguration
extends Object
implements Cloneable
    Configuration for a generic filter that can includes and excludes names and takes care on additional/missing names using the enforce inclusion/exclusion option. It also supports filtering based on name patterns.

    This class may contain additional functionality in future versions. Clients should not rely on the enforce in/exclusion flags but only use the standard load/save routines and the applyTo(String[]) method.

    Since:
    2.6
    Author:
    Thomas Gabriel, KNIME.com AG, Zurich, Switzerland, Patrick Winter, KNIME.com AG, Zurich, Switzerland

      • NameFilterConfiguration

        public NameFilterConfiguration(String configRootName,
                               int filterEnableMask)
        Creates a new name filter configuration with the given settings name. The flags argument enables or disables certain filter types. Currently, this filter only supports FILTER_BY_NAMEPATTERN.
        Parameters:
        configRootName - the config name to used to store the settings
        filterEnableMask - The mask to enable filters. 0 will disable all filters but the default in/exclude; FILTER_BY_NAMEPATTERN will enable the name pattern filter.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - If config name is null or empty
        Since:
        2.9

      • loadDefaults

        protected void loadDefaults(String[] names,
                            boolean includeByDefault)
        Sets default names, used in auto-configure of a node when no settings are available.
        Parameters:
        names - The input names
        includeByDefault - If true, all elements will be put into the include list and the "enforce exclusion" will be set. Otherwise all elements are put into the exclude list and the "enforce inclusion" is set. If in doubt, pass true here.

      • getType

        protected final String getType()
        The type identifier of the actual filter implementation. This can be the default include/exclude list, a name pattern filter or something defined by the subclass. Default is TYPE ("STANDARD") but can also be PatternFilterConfigurationImpl.TYPE or something else (subclasses can add more type filters).
        Returns:
        the type, not null.
        Since:
        2.9

      • verifyType

        protected boolean verifyType(String type)

        Parameters:
        type - The type identifier
        Returns:
